        "MissionType#Id": 0,
        "MissionTask": "SITREP (CAO 02 May): The JECC KM team provided an IPR to the JPSE Commander on 28 April 2023 and prepared a Bullet Background Paper (BBP) for submission to the DJ7 and to the JECC/CC prior to this Thursday’s IPR.\n\n3.2. (U) CURRENT OPERATIONS: The JPSE KM team has begun the production phase of the mission. Mr. Cosimo and LCDR John Roberts are back at the Pentagon concluding interviews, conducting follow-up interviews, and preparing for the IPR with the DJ7. \n\n3.3. (U) FUTURE OPERATIONS: MTP personnel will complete interviews with the DJ7 staff, conduct the second IPR with the DJ7, and return to the JECC (Building X-132) to finalize products for the final IPR and product delivery. CAPT Culver, JPSE KM Functional Group Lead, will travel to the Pentagon on 4 May 2023 to take part in the IPR and MG Jost has been invited to dial in via VTC. The production process is currently scheduled for approximately two weeks. Once complete, the team will return to the Pentagon, tentatively scheduled for 18 or 19 May, to provide products and back brief the DJ7. Finally, the DJ7 has requested the MTP provide a briefing to the J7 senior staff at the upcoming off-site tentatively scheduled for the end of June 2023 as well as a follow-on Knowledge Manager’s Practitioner’s Course (KMPC)for J7 team members.\n \nSITREP (CAO 25 Apr): The MTP met with the DCG & received additional planning guidance related to the MA of the JTRU. Our primary focus is more on defining what is the best construct of Reserve capability for HQ, USTRANSCOM rather than solely focusing on an organizational change to the command structure. Additionally, the DCG directed us to stand-up a temporary working group to further analyze what the best Reserve construct could be. We will also begin providing an update on the JTRU Mission Analysis during the Chief of Staff’s weekly action board until the MA brief is given to the DCG. \n\n3.1. (U) EFFORTS COMPLETED TO DATE: Received additional planning guidance from USTC DCOM on 21 Apr 23 for the analysis of the JTRU. Liaised with the Historian, USTRANSCOM on 20 Apr 23 to receive more historical documentation on the JTRU. Met with J6, USTRANSCOM to understand and document how they have historically utilized reservists from the JTRU. Continued to prepare MA Brief to the DCG.\n\n3.2. (U) CURRENT OPERATIONS: JTRU Working Group discussions scheduled for this week.\n\n3.3. (U) FUTURE OPERATIONS: Touchpoints scheduled with the CoS & DCOM, USTRANSCOM on Wednesday and Friday of this week to provide an update on our analysis.\n\nSITREP (CAO 18 Apr): JECC KM team held a VTC with the mission partner to discuss future timelines and operations. Continuing interviews and discovery at Suffolk and will begin winding down the interview process with key staff members and transition to the production phase of the MTP.\n\nSITREP (CAO 11 Apr): KM team continues drafting the Information Flow Diagram (IFD), Process Maps, &observations/considerations. Moreover the JECC KM team provided a status update to the JECC CDR. MTP personnel will complete interviews and will begin building products. This process is currently scheduled for approximately two weeks. Once complete, the team will most likely return to the Pentagon to complete interviews (if required) refine products and back brief the Director, J7.",

        "MissionType#Id": 3,
        "MissionTask": "SITREP (CAO 18 Apr): AS PREVIOUSLY NOTED IN CCIR #1, VIGILANT SHIELD ’23 UNEXPECTEDLY ENDED THE AFTERNOON OF 16 APRIL. PA AND FIRES/TARGETING TEAMS WERE ABLE TO SUCCESSFULLY PIVOT TO TRAINING AND REAL-WORLD DOCUMENTS TO ASSIST BOTH TRAINING OBJECTIVES AND USEFULL PRODUCTS FOR PA AND THE JOINT FIRES DIVISION. THE 3/5 SECTION HAD NO SUCH POST-EXERCISE ITEMS FOR THE FOUR JPSE PERSONNEL. AS A RESULT, TWO PLANNERS WERE RELEASED EARLY, AND THE OTHER TWO PERSONNEL WERE THE JPSE TEAM LEAD AND DEPUTY, WHO STARTED EVAL AND AAR PROCESSES.\n\nSunday afternoon at about 1400 hrs, we unexpectedly received word of a “PauseEx” on VS ’23. However, in discussion with ARNORTH members, it seemed very likely that the “PauseEx” would become an “EndEx” in as far as VS ’23 was concerned. This morning, I confirmed that – as far as normal exercise play – VS 23 was concluded.",

        "MissionType#Id": 3,
        "MissionTask": "SITREP (CAO 25 Apr): The components have the lead on CAP while the ECJ35 team works to integrate the subordinate plans. The J35 has been very distracted due to current events which caused a few days of shifted support from AC23; the MTP kept the AC23 planning on track. Anticipated start date of CPX is 4 MAY.\n\n3.1. (U) EFFORTS COMPLETED TO DATE: Supported COA development briefing, COA comparison, wargaming, and developed draft Level 1 Commander’s Estimate and PLANORD.\n\n3.2. (U) CURRENT OPERATIONS: Team developed script, framework, and decision support template for the wargame that will be conducted on 25 APR 23. The wargame will be action officer level only due to EUCOM decision based on leadership availability and time.\n\n3.3. (U) FUTURE OPERATIONS: Plan to conduct COA decision brief on 27 or 28 APR depending on the COM’s schedule and finalize the PLANORD for transition to J33. 2x members (Garvin, Uban) will return to home of record on 29 APR 23.\n\nSITREP (CAO 18 Apr): The team is on ground and link in well with the EC J35 team. Today we developed COA sketches for tomorrow’s prebrief with the J3 as well as assisting the J25 with ECOAs & EDSM. I’ve mitigated the lack of the intel planner bu splitting my time with the J35 & J25 while the rest of the team works with the J35. No issues. J35’s focus is clearly taken up by real world issues. They fully understand the process & costs if they want the MTP to support something else. I don’t foresee that happening at the moment.\n\n(CAO 17 Apr): On 14 Apr, based on a higher-priority, emerging mission requirement, JPSE initiated a CCIR1 to account for the Intel Planner shortfall (BG Hamilton approved). The remaining planners successfully deployed & began RSOI on 17 Apr. No mission impacting issues identified.",

        "MissionTask": "SITREP (CAO 02 May): The team arrived 29-30 APR 23. On 1 MAY 23 they completed inprocessing, integration into respective JDIRs, and onboarding for the exercise. \n\n3.2. (U) CURRENT OPERATIONS: USEUCOM is conducting transition activies from CAP to CPX as well as onboarding of exercise augmentation. Team is supporting staff planning efforts to prepare for the start of the CPX on 5 MAY 23.\n\n3.3. (U) FUTURE OPERATIONS: Team will participate in EUCOM J3 component backbrief on Thursday, 4 MAY 23, and continue to assist respective JDIRs in preperation and product production for CPX execution.   \n\n\n*Update* (CAO 21 Apr) Lt Col Danielle Johnson (Ops) will replace Maj Ditmer (Ops) based on Maj Ditmer's security clearance. Lt Col Johnson will transition to Oberammergau, Germany for the NATO COPC after AC23 CPX.\n\n(CAO 17 Apr) MAJ Reddenbaugh (Ops) will now fulfill the Intel Planner role w/ECJ2.         "MissionType#Id": 0,
        "MissionTask": "SITREP (CAO 25 Apr 21): The MTP met with the DCG & received additional planning guidance related to the MA of the JTRU. Our primary focus is more on defining what is the best construct of Reserve capability for HQ, USTRANSCOM rather than solely focusing on an organizational change to the command structure. Additionally, the DCG directed us to stand-up a temporary working group to further analyze what the best Reserve construct could be. We will also begin providing an update on the JTRU Mission Analysis during the Chief of Staff’s weekly action board until the MA brief is given to the DCG. \n\n3.1. (U) EFFORTS COMPLETED TO DATE: Received additional planning guidance from USTC DCOM on 21 Apr 23 for the analysis of the JTRU. Liaised with the Historian, USTRANSCOM on 20 Apr 23 to receive more historical documentation on the JTRU. Met with J6, USTRANSCOM to understand and document how they have historically utilized reservists from the JTRU. Continued to prepare MA Brief to the DCG.\n\n3.2. (U) CURRENT OPERATIONS: JTRU Working Group discussions scheduled for this week.\n\n3.3. (U) FUTURE OPERATIONS: Touchpoints scheduled with the CoS & DCOM, USTRANSCOM on Wednesday and Friday of this week to provide an update on our analysis.\n\nSITREP (CAO 18 Apr 21): Finalized our POA&M and we continue to dialog and discuss the way-ahead with key leaders within USTRANSCOM to understand the problem set regarding the construct of the JTRU and the utilization of Reserve capability within HQ, USTRANCOM. These key leader engagements continue to reveal relevant facts and assumptions that we will have to validate in order to develop, analyze and compare the potential COAs we have identified, so far. Additionally, we continue to review key historical documents associated with the JTRU and define the meaning of key words to further support our analysis. \n\n3.1. (U) EFFORTS COMPLETED TO DATE: Met with Chief of Staff, HQ, USTRANSCOM on 12 Apr 23 to receive initial guidance for the analayis of the JTRU. Met with former JA on 13 Apr 23 and discussed his previous legal opinion regarding the JTRC Commander position. Mr. Werner provided historical documentation relevant to the subject matter. Met with the J1, USTRANSCOM and the Sennior Leader Management Office to discuss possible changes to the position decription of the JTRU Commander position based on potential JTRU organizational structural changes. \n\n3.2. (U) CURRENT OPERATIONS: We continue to work on describing the current OE, identify facts, and develop assumptions relevant to the JTRU construct and utilization of the Reserve force, as well as determining and analyzing any limtiations which would lead us to develop a streamlined op approach and identify the salient problem USTRANSCOM wants to solve through this analysis.  \n\n3.3. (U) FUTURE OPERATIONS: Will meet with current JTRU Commander, the Deputy J6, USTRANSCOM on Wednesday and Thursday of this week to gain further understand their perspective of the JTRU construct and utilization of Reserve capability. Will also meet with the Chief of Staff, USTRANSCOM this week to provide an update on our analysis.  \n\n\nMovement Report (CAO 10 Apr): COL Molina and MAJ Boland (JPSE) departed HOR and arrived at Scott AFB, IL ",

        "MissionType#Id": 0,
        "MissionTask": "SITREP (CAO 02 May): Last week leadership within CDAO reoriented the MTP on 2 specific tasks they’d like accomplished in the upcoming 6 weeks: Task 1. Implement in GIDE 6 a means to digitally collaborate and improve senior leader risk analysis for globally integrated planning and decision-making with a specific emphasis on GFM and 2nd and 3rd order effects of FDO/FRO execution on the Joint Force (output a digital SDOB); and Task 2. Plan for GIDE 7 (execution in SEP 23) in conjunction with the BOLD QUEST and JS J7 JTF Next effort.  Additionally, the MTP participated in the GIDE 6 MPC, 26-27 APR 23.  During the MPC the mission partner ensured, repeatedly, that all GIDE participants (Joint Staff Directorates and all CCMDs) understood that the JECC was leading the Global Integration and GFM portion of GIDE 6.\n\n3.2. (U) CURRENT OPERATIONS: The MTP is working with various Joint Staff Directorates and defense contractors to determine the critical workflows associated with Task #1 and develop an approach to link disparate systems and data together within GIDE 6 to approximate the critical path.\n\n3.3. (U) FUTURE OPERATIONS: The MTP will focus primarily on Task #1 in this week.   The MTP lead will develop a rough GIDE 7 plan for initial staffing with the CDAO team NLT 12 MAY 23 with the intent of transitioning the GIDE 7 planning to the mission’s second tranche of JECC support beginning o/a 15 MAY 23.\n\nSITREP (CAO 25 Apr): The CDAO team is a small group that is caught in a constant execution cycle.  They have been unable to remove themselves from the immediate fray and examine their experimentation plan and evaluate its ability to achieve the desired objectives.  The MTP brings a fresh set of eyes and a relatively unbiased viewpoint to the problem.  The next few weeks will be spent in a furious rush to publish the experimentation plan with accompanying GENADMIN message and PLANORD as well as overseeing the contract team from George Mason University responsible for scenario design and exercise control.  Finally, no later than early next week the MTP will provide JPSE/JECC with recommendations for sourcing the mission’s second tranche currently scheduled for 15 May – 30 Sep.\n\n3.1. (U) PRODUCTS/EFFORTS COMPLETED TO DATE: The team completed initial in-processing, badging, and network account set-up.  Additionally, team members began the process of familiarizing themselves with JADC2 and GIDE products.\n\n3.2. (U) CURRENT OPERATIONS: Team members are assisting in the development of the GIDE VI experimentation plan by crafting scenario injects to drive CCMD exercise participants through a series of digital planning and decision-making processes.\n\n3.3. (U) FUTURE OPERATIONS: The team will participate in the GIDE VI Main Planning Conference (MPC) 26-27APR23.\n\n(CAO 17 Apr) LTC Bet will depart for Arlington, VA on 20 Apr to facilitate his ACFT. MAJ An is already on station (HOR), but is not working in an official capacity w/the mission partner until LTC Bet's arrival. ",

        "MissionType#Id": 2,
        "MissionTask": "CAO 20JUN: 11-16 Jun: Site vists to DHS activities in CA and AZ IOT: (i) compare and contrast movement operations in these sectors with those observed in previous visits to sectors to the East, (ii) identify knowledge and operational gaps between field and national-level decision making bodies, and (iii) assess capabilities and procedures for ICE/ERO air operations, which is a key chokepoint, at close hand.\n\n3.2. (U) CURRENT OPERATIONS: Continue deep dive analysis of three cross-functional areas (ground movement, air movement, and associated information management) within Mission Partner’s non-citizen movement operation for identification of gaps, and formulation of recommendations to improve efficiency.\n\nCAO JUN: MTP members visited DHS activities in El Paso and supported interviews with SBCC personnel involved in planning movement of non-citizens.  The team briefed an Operational Approach to Mission Partner leadership.  The MTP Team Lead swaps out this week.\nConduct process analysis and optimization plans that focus on logistics of current noncitizen processing, movement of noncitizens from points of apprehension, transportation of noncitizens, and U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement, Planning and coordination of logistics at the regional and headquarters levels.\nCAO 3MAY: Expect mission to be IRF/RFF and 90-120 days in duration. Expected in-place date 10 May. Technical advice and assistance from 4xGPs from the Joint Enabling Capabilities Command (JECC) or similar DOD resource.",

        "MissionTask": "Why: (Planners) Based on lessons learned from the Nov ‘21 spill, intent is to develop a crisis response plan for the Joint Force/USINDOPACOM in case of a catastrophic spill during defueling. (PA) Knowing there will be significant local and national media attention during defueling, intent is to increase capacity for PA related tasks (press releases & conferences, visual information, media queries, and updates to web, social and app).\n\nWeek 1: Indoc, inbrief, familiarization. I think we can pre-brief the team before they depart to shorten this step.\nWeek 2-3: Planning conference/OPT work. This will be the meat of the mission and involve gathering information from the various J-dirs and partners, of which there are many (CNRH, IPC, NAVFAC, NAVSUP, FEDFIRE, DHA, PACFLT, USARPAC, etc).\nWeek 3-4: Orders writing/dev.\nWeek 5: Brief to CC.\n",

        "MissionType#Id": 0,
        "MissionTask": "CAO 20JUN:Received the log-in information for JWICS accounts that should allow JOWPD to grant share drive access, however on-site hardware issues and the current ops tempo have prevented us from running the access issue to ground. Pending other issues, CDR Conklin and CAPT Chin should be good on JWICS by the time they arrive.  I anticipate the full team will have both the accounts and access needed once the hardware issues are resolved by the on-site help desk.  \n\nThe MTP continues to support the JOWPD staff on CPG coordination and JSCP revision. The MTP is working to help absorb the dynamic workload and deadlines flowing from OSD and the CJCS along the three lines of effort below. While the CPG is currently JOWPD’s primary focus, the JSCP revision is the greatest concern as the staffing timeline is very compressed and directly dependent, in part, on the results of continuing coordination on the GEF and CPG\n\nWHO: Joint Staff J5/JSP/Joint Operational War Plans Division (JOWPD)\nWHAT: Four (4) Joint planners with campaign and contingency planning experience and current active JWICS accounts\nWHEN: 22 May to 31 August 2023 (102 days).\nWHERE: 4 planners on-site at the Pentagon\nWHY: Provide planning support to complete short-suspense revisions to the Joint Strategic Campaign Plan to align with campaign and contingency planning guidance in the Guidance for the Employment of the Force (GEF) and the Contingency Planning Guidance (CPG) and meet CJCS directed completion timeline by the end of August 2023. The JECC planners will analyze and revise the JSCP campaign approach relative to the GEF, develop written campaign and contingency planning guidance for the JSCP, and generate briefing products to enable a series of three Operations Deputies Meetings and JCS TANKs.  The JECC planners will assist JOWPD Strategic Guidance Branch in generating CJCS-level briefing products and memoranda that will enable CJCS to formally provide his advice on the GEF and CPG and finalize his implementation guidance for both documents through the JSCP. ",

        "MissionTask": "This event gathers Joint Petroleum stakeholders from the Combatant Commands, DLA (Energy), and Industry partners to discuss multiple issues impacting the procurement, storage, distribution, and authorities required for Class III(B) during competition, crisis, and conflict.         "MissionType#Id": 0,
        "MissionTask": "The Joint Staff Director for Joint Force Development (DJ-7) is directing a Solarium-type event to gather feedback on portions of revised doctrine. The purpose of the Solarium is to evaluate proposed current doctrine for sufficiency and identify emergent learning from on-going operations, training, testing, and experimentation that is proving advantageous for the future Joint Force. The Solarium members will review the signature drafts of Joint Publication (JP) 3-30 Joint Air Operations; JP 3-53, Military Information Support Operations; and JP 3-60, Joint Targeting. Requesting 0-4s and 0-5s to evaluate each draft for sufficiency, consider on-going learning from on-going force development, and provide input for future doctrinal concepts and considerations.",

        "SupportRequests": "JPSE will conduct a staff ride to key events of the War of 1812 Chesapeake Campaign. To give senior JPSE officers an opportunity to lead a discussion and training, the staff rides end state is to give JPSE participants a better understanding of how the factors of Joint tactical and operational actions lead to strategic outcomes in Joint Operations. JPSE officers will apply their knowledge of the elements of Operational Art and Design and Joint Functions to a significant historical campaign in military history, understand general officer leadership at the operational level of war, and to better understand the role of joint functions in modern warfare.  Functional groups balance JRF mission support requirements with joint training opportunities and nominate 3-5 members per FG to attend the training.",

        "MissionTask": " Overview: The Joint Planning Support Elements (JPSE) Knowledge Management (KM) Class is intended to establish a KM foundation for Joint Enabling Capabilities Command (JECC) active and reserve component personnel but is open to other DoD organizations on a space available basis. The class is offered quarterly to fulfill JPSE training needs.\n\nThe class provides a solid foundation covering the major concepts, techniques, skills, and capabilities associated with KM and the JPSE KM implementation plan in support of the JECC’s Joint Force Headquarters support mission. Attendees will be familiarized with the \"why\" and \"how\" JPSE KM implements its deliberate approach to establishing effective staff processes in order to achieve and maintain effective decision support for the commander and shared staff understanding.  \n",
